better-bow:
    "One day a disciple asked Master Canaro: “Master, which kind of bow shoots best?”<br />
    The master answered: “The one you use every day.”<br />
    The disciple then asked: “Master, does this mean one could use an unsuitable programming language, as long as the goal is reached?”<br />
    The master smiled benevolently and said: “Please, go meditate on the senselessness of your questions while you clean the common latrines.”<br />
    For a long time I couldn't understand Master Canaro's behavior. For a while, I believed the error lay in that “best” in the first question, and that the master had deliberately given an imprecise answer in order to carry a poorly framed line of reasoning to its extreme conclusions, but I was wrong.<br />
    The truth was that Master Canaro, as he himself confessed to me, was trying to offload his turn at cleaning the latrines onto someone else, and the young and impetuous disciple had given him the opportunity.<br />"

