computer-aunt:
    "One day, Master Canaro's aunt called him and told him her computer had stopped working.<br />
    “It turns on, but it won't connect to the Internet and it can't send email. Please, come and fix it.”<br />
    So Master Canaro went to his aunt's house and asked her to show him the computer that wasn't working.
    His aunt led him into her study and turned on the laptop sitting on the desk.
    As expected, the computer started up normally, but when Master Canaro tried to open the browser, an error message appeared.
    The Master then tried to open the email program, but once again an error message appeared.<br />
    Under his aunt's increasingly anguished gaze, Master Canaro examined the network settings, checked that the modem was working, and updated the system files, but the problem remained; so, the Master picked up the computer and threw it out the window.<br />
    “What have you done?!” his aunt exclaimed, aghast.<br />
    “It wasn't working, so I threw it out,” the Master answered.<br />
    “But couldn't it have been fixed?” his aunt asked, still unable to grasp what had happened.<br />
    “Maybe, but it would have taken a lot of time: better to throw it away.”<br />
    “And how am I supposed to work now, without a computer?” his aunt asked, stunned. Master Canaro shrugged.<br />
    “No idea, but you couldn't have worked with that one either, since it was broken.”<br />
    “I know it was broken!” his aunt exclaimed. “But when something necessary is broken, you fix it, you don't throw it away!”<br />
    Far from looking contrite, Master Canaro stood up and, staring his aunt in the eye, exclaimed:<br />
    “And what about you people, back in '68?!”"

