universe-cpp:
    "<h3>Last page of Master Canaro's diary (April 8)</h3> I'm at the office, working, when the phone rings. The voice that answers is rather deep and has a curious echo.
    It says:
    <br />-&nbsp;Canaro, it's God, I need you.
    <br />-&nbsp;Marco, I'm busy, talk later.
    <br />I hang up. A moment later the phone rings again. This time I pay attention to the type of ring and deduce it's an outside call.
    <br />-&nbsp;Canaro, I'm not your colleague, I really am God. I need you to help me port the universe to C++.
    <br />I can't help but smile.
    <br />-&nbsp;Cute. And the voice synthesizer seems to work pretty well too. Look, let me finish this report and I'll buy you a coffee, but let me work for now.
    <br />I hang up again, and again the wretched thing makes its voice heard. It's an outside line, I can't risk it: it could be a client, but I already know that..
    <br />-&nbsp;Canaro, listen to me once and for all: I really am God and I need you to solve a problem for me.
    <br />I'm about to say something I'll regret, but the voice goes on:
    <br />-&nbsp;If you don't believe me, unplug the phone.
    <br />-&nbsp;Oh, come on..
    <br />-&nbsp;Unplug it!
    <br /> More out of curiosity than anything else, I decide to call the bluff. I unplug it.
    <br />-&nbsp;Do you believe me now?
    <br /> I have to admit that for a moment my skepticism wavers. I look for a possible explanation.
    <br />-&nbsp;You put a receiver in the handset.
    <br />-&nbsp;Stubborn, eh? All right: pick a random object.
    <br />-&nbsp;To do what?
    <br />-&nbsp;To use as a handset, one your colleague couldn't have tampered with.
    <br />-&nbsp;Marco, please..
    <br />-&nbsp;Come on, what does it cost you? Since you're so sure..
    <br />-&nbsp;Is my pipe okay?
    <br />-&nbsp;Whatever you like: hold it up to your ear.
    <br />Let's see where he's going with this: I take my pipe out of its leather case and hold the bowl up to my ear.
    <br />-&nbsp;Done, -&nbsp;I say, and meanwhile I look around, waiting for the prank.
    <br />-&nbsp;I know, -&nbsp;the voice is in the briar bowl. -&nbsp;Now, if we could please get back to our phone conversation.. I wouldn't want someone to walk in and see you talking to a pipe.
    <br />
    <br />-&nbsp;Let me start by saying I don't understand anything about these computer things, -&nbsp; he tells me as soon as I've plugged the phone back in.
    <br />-&nbsp;My son, on the other hand, knows how to use computers, and he told me it would be better to port the universe to an object-oriented language, suggesting this C++. Now, you see, I'm strong in the natural sciences, not in computer science, and all these technical terms are a mystery to me: what does it mean to port something? And what are object-oriented languages?
    <br />
    “Good question,” I thought. Years earlier I had written a C++ manual, and the object-oriented paradigm was the subject of the first chapter. If only he had read it..
    <br />-&nbsp;I also skimmed through your book, but I didn't understand a thing: you write terribly, let me tell you. And then, I thought, who knows how many things have changed in the meantime, so I decided to call you.
    <br />-&nbsp;First of all, thank you for the compliments, and then, to answer your question, porting something means rewriting an application in a programming language different from the one it was originally written in.
    <br />-&nbsp;And what's the purpose of that?
    <br />-&nbsp;Usually to take advantage of the new language's capabilities, or to be able to use the application on a system where the old language isn't supported.
    <br />-&nbsp;Like translating the ten commandments from Hebrew into Latin?
    <br />-&nbsp;Something like that.
    <br />-&nbsp;And this “C++”? What does “object-oriented language” mean?
    <br />-&nbsp;That instead of abstract data types like numbers and characters, it lets you use data types more similar to real things.
    <br />-&nbsp;I don't understand.
    <br />-&nbsp;Old programming languages forced the programmer to use only predefined data types: numbers, letters, dates. That's fine for a certain kind of application, but it makes it hard to write more complex applications where it can help to have a language capable of handling new, user-defined data types as well. In C++, the language your son recommended to you, this is achieved by means of classes.
    <br />-&nbsp;Like in zoology?
    <br />-&nbsp;Sort of. By class we mean a non-standard data type, for which you can define the behavior.
    <br />-&nbsp;Give me an example, I don't get it. And also, enough with this formal “you”, let's switch to the informal one, it's simpler.
    <br />-&nbsp;Let's say you have two strings..
    <br />-&nbsp;I don't wear shoes with strings, I wear Birkenstock sandals.
    <br />-&nbsp;I meant sequences of characters. Now, in the way a computer normally handles data, it makes no sense to add two strings together, since it's not a numeric data type, but you can define a “String” class that, if subjected to addition, does something sensible.
    <br />-&nbsp;Like what?
    <br />-&nbsp;Suppose you have any string A.
    <br />-&nbsp;Is “Foo” okay?
    <br />-&nbsp;Original. And suppose you want to join it to another string B.
    <br />-&nbsp;“Bar”.
    <br />-&nbsp;Also quite original. Anyway, you would write the instruction: C = A + B, and string C would contain: “FooBar”.
    <br />-&nbsp;I'll keep that in mind the next time I need to write “FooBar”.
    <br />-&nbsp;It was an example.
    <br />-&nbsp;I still don't get why they're called “object-oriented languages”.
    <br />-&nbsp;Because they don't handle raw data, but objects with a well-defined behavior of their own.
    <br />-&nbsp;I need to see it in practice. Anyway, what would be the advantages of this translation?
    <br />-&nbsp;In the case of C++, easier analysis.
    <br />-&nbsp;But the analysis of the application already exists.
    <br />-&nbsp;And easier debugging.
    <br />-&nbsp;Sorry?
    <br />-&nbsp;Fixing errors.
    <br />-&nbsp;The current application has been running forever and has never given any problems.
    <br />-&nbsp;It also increases the chances of reusing the code in other applications.
    <br />-&nbsp;That sounds about as useful as the string “FooBar”.
    <br />-&nbsp;Does the production process have a quality certification?
    <br />-&nbsp;I saw that it was good: I'd say that's enough.
    <br />-&nbsp;Well, then I don't see any need to rewrite it.
    <br />-&nbsp;That's exactly what I told my son, but he started
    talking about this C++ and that other thing, the one named after an island, what's it called..
    <br />-&nbsp;Java? It's not named after an island, but after a type of coffee blend.
    <br />-&nbsp;Whatever it is. The point is: what's the need to rewrite everything?
    <br />-&nbsp;As far as I can tell, I'd say none..
    <br />-&nbsp;Good, thank you.
    <br />
    He hangs up (or whatever it is), but after a while he calls back.
    <br />-&nbsp;Canaro, I talked to my son and he says I'm old-fashioned, that the current application is obsolete, that users are complaining, and that this port is necessary. I don't understand anything anymore, what should I do?
    <br />
    I'm about to answer “God only knows”, but fortunately I hold back and resort to the standard answer for these cases:
    <br />-&nbsp;We could do a feasibility study and then decide..
    <br />-&nbsp;Sounds like a good idea. When can you start?
    <br />-&nbsp;I don't know, I have to ask my manager.
    <br />-&nbsp;All right: ask him and let me know.
    <br />
    He hangs up without telling me how I'm supposed to “let him know”, but that's the least of my problems. The first one, right now, is how to tell my boss about this without being taken for a madman.
    <br />
    <br />-&nbsp;If you're hoping to get some sick leave for a nervous breakdown, forget it. You've said (and above all done) far stranger things.
    <br />-&nbsp;I know it's crazy, but it's true: God called me and asked me to rewrite the Universe in C++.
    <br />-&nbsp;Canaro, cut it out and go finish the analysis, we have to bring it to the client this afternoon.
    <br />-&nbsp;And if he calls me again, what should I tell him?
    <br />-&nbsp;Tell him how badly you got the estimates wrong on the last project, so he'll go to someone else.
    <br />
